Now, I will first find the point of intersection of the two lines in terms of $t.$
There is a unique ordered pair $(x, y)$ for each real number $t$ that satisfies both line equations as shown below.
\begin{align*}
x + 2y &= 7t + 3 \quad \text{(1)} \\
x - y &= 2t - 2 \quad \text{(2)} \\
\end{align*}
Adding $2$ times equation $(2)$ to equation $(1):$
\begin{align*}
3x &= 11t + 1 \\
x &= \tfrac{11}{3}t + \tfrac{1}{3} \\
\end{align*}
Plugging this into equation $(2):$
\begin{align*}
\tfrac{11}{3}t + \tfrac{1}{3} - y &= 2t - 2 \\
y &= \tfrac{11}{3}t + \tfrac{1}{3} - 2t + 2 \\
y &= \tfrac{5}{3}t + \tfrac{7}{3} \\
\end{align*}
Therefore, all points have the shape $(\tfrac{11}{3}t + \tfrac{1}{3}, \tfrac{5}{3}t + \tfrac{7}{3})$</think> <answer>$$\frac{\frac{5}{3}t + \frac{7}{3}}{\frac{11}{3}t + \frac{1}{3}} = \frac{5t + 7}{11t + 1}$$
To finish the problem, I need a piecewise-defined function with two pieces, $(\displaystyle\frac{5t+7}{11t+1})\chi_A(t) + (\frac{5t+7}{11t+1})\chi_B(t)$ such that $(11t+1)$ never equals zero, i.e., $$11t+1 \neq 0$$
So, the line in question is $$\boxed{x = \frac{5}{11}y + \frac{68}{11}}$$</answer>

